WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:16.660
Hey there, welcome to the Posit Data Science Hangout. I'm Libby Heron, and this is a recording

00:00:16.660 --> 00:00:22.020
of our weekly community call that happens every Thursday at 12pm US Eastern Time. If

00:00:22.020 --> 00:00:27.260
you are not joining us live, you miss out on the amazing chat that's going on. So find

00:00:27.260 --> 00:00:30.719
the link in the description where you can add our call to your calendar and come hang

00:00:30.719 --> 00:00:36.340
out with the most supportive, friendly, and funny data community you'll ever experience.

00:00:36.340 --> 00:00:42.320
Can't wait to see you there. I want to go ahead and introduce our featured leaders today

00:00:42.320 --> 00:00:48.840
because we have two and they are both keynote at Posit Conf, which is really exciting. So

00:00:48.840 --> 00:00:53.959
we have Kieran Healy, Professor of Sociology at Duke University, and we also have Jonathan

00:00:53.959 --> 00:01:01.180
McPherson, Software Architect at Posit. Say hi to everybody. I am going to ask Kieran

00:01:01.180 --> 00:01:07.580
to go ahead and introduce yourself first. A little bit of background about Kieran and

00:01:07.580 --> 00:01:11.620
something you would like to do for fun outside of work.

00:01:11.620 --> 00:01:16.660
Hi everyone, and thanks for coming. There's a big crowd here. My name is Kieran Healy.

00:01:16.720 --> 00:01:23.720
As Libby said, I teach Sociology at Duke here in North Carolina. I'm originally from Ireland

00:01:23.720 --> 00:01:29.720
and I've been using, as I like to say, I've been using R since it was a different letter,

00:01:29.720 --> 00:01:34.879
since it was S. Back as a graduate student, I was introduced to it by one of my teachers

00:01:34.879 --> 00:01:40.639
and since then it's been sort of the main way that I do data analysis and teach it and

00:01:40.639 --> 00:01:47.699
draw pictures with it. And kind of over the years, having just being a user of it, I've

00:01:47.699 --> 00:01:52.419
become somebody who also writes about it and tries to teach people how to use it specifically

00:01:52.419 --> 00:01:56.779
with data visualization. So that's my background with R.

00:01:56.779 --> 00:01:58.980
And anything for fun?

00:01:58.980 --> 00:02:05.540
Anything for fun? Being Irish, I'm just naturally averse to those kinds of questions. I restore

00:02:05.540 --> 00:02:09.380
old computers. How about that? I build those things that you can see in the background.

00:02:09.399 --> 00:02:17.279
I rehabilitate in my basement vintage computers and then occasionally threaten my students

00:02:17.279 --> 00:02:24.119
with having them run their their analyses on them whenever they complain about running

00:02:24.119 --> 00:02:25.880
out of memory or something like that.

00:02:25.880 --> 00:02:28.479
Does it does it pain you to call them vintage?

00:02:28.479 --> 00:02:30.000
Because it pains me.

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:32.679
It does, yeah, because that means I'm vintage.

00:02:32.679 --> 00:02:35.399
Right. Yeah. I mean, I'm like, well, these are the things I had as a kid.

00:02:35.399 --> 00:02:38.399
They can't possibly be vintage.

00:02:38.419 --> 00:02:41.139
Wonderful. I'm going to have Jonathan do the same thing.

00:02:41.139 --> 00:02:42.820
Jonathan, could you introduce yourself?

00:02:42.820 --> 00:02:46.619
Tell us a little bit about you, how you got here and something you like to do for fun.

00:02:47.820 --> 00:02:48.899
Yeah. Hey, everybody.

00:02:48.899 --> 00:02:53.300
I'm Jonathan. I'm coming at you live from the Seattle area of Washington, where it is

00:02:53.300 --> 00:02:54.899
still morning. I still need coffee.

00:02:55.740 --> 00:02:58.779
I'm a software engineer and architect at Posit.

00:02:59.179 --> 00:03:04.100
I'm not a data scientist, to be clear, but I do make tools for data scientists.

00:03:04.320 --> 00:03:09.679
So I was fortunate enough to be one of the early employees at RStudio, now Posit, and

00:03:09.679 --> 00:03:12.759
have worked for most of my time here on the RStudio IDE.

00:03:13.240 --> 00:03:18.039
If you have not used RStudio, it is one of the first and, in my opinion, still one of

00:03:18.039 --> 00:03:20.000
the best IDEs for the R language.

00:03:20.919 --> 00:03:25.240
A couple of years ago, I switched gears and helped create a new IDE called Positron,

00:03:25.240 --> 00:03:29.839
which kind of takes a lot of the ideas from RStudio and develops them into a bigger,

00:03:29.960 --> 00:03:31.919
more ambitious multi-language IDE.

00:03:32.100 --> 00:03:37.380
So I'd love to take questions about RStudio, Positron, data science tools, software

00:03:37.380 --> 00:03:38.779
engineering and architecture, and so on.

00:03:39.740 --> 00:03:41.300
For fun, I am a dad.

00:03:41.539 --> 00:03:44.539
I have three kids, so I spend a lot of time with them.

00:03:44.820 --> 00:03:46.460
I'm into music. I play the piano.

00:03:47.220 --> 00:03:50.020
I read a lot of books. I go through at least a few books a month.

00:03:50.139 --> 00:03:52.179
Fiction, nonfiction, everything in between.

00:03:52.740 --> 00:03:56.820
And I also ride my bicycle a lot, so that's me.

00:03:57.500 --> 00:04:00.259
I go through a lot of books every month, too, and then I tell myself, I don't have time

00:04:00.279 --> 00:04:04.880
for anything. I don't have time to read a lot of books.

00:04:06.320 --> 00:04:11.279
All right. Well, I wanted to give us a chance to sort of preview both of your

00:04:11.679 --> 00:04:16.040
conf talks. This is putting pressure on you because you might not even have your conf

00:04:16.040 --> 00:04:21.119
talks done. I have given a talk at conf and I was not ready months before, but

00:04:21.399 --> 00:04:26.920
I thought maybe we could do a pseudo abstract for each of you just so that it gives

00:04:26.920 --> 00:04:28.320
us all a little bit more context.

00:04:28.660 --> 00:04:32.820
Kieran, would you like to go first and talk a little bit about what you plan to talk

00:04:32.820 --> 00:04:33.820
about in your keynote?

00:04:34.459 --> 00:04:39.700
Sure. Yes. And my talk is certainly not done at this stage.

00:04:40.540 --> 00:04:45.019
My talk will be about trustworthy data visualization.

00:04:45.859 --> 00:04:51.019
As I said a minute ago, I'm interested in data visualization because it's such a

00:04:51.019 --> 00:04:55.540
powerful way to condense and present information, often tremendous amounts of

00:04:55.540 --> 00:05:00.720
information, into sort of a compelling and seemingly authoritative, often beautiful

00:05:00.720 --> 00:05:04.119
artifact that travels really well, that you can show to people and convince people of

00:05:04.119 --> 00:05:08.959
things with. And now, in a way, all of statistics, all of the things that we produce

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:13.399
with data science models and tables and all the rest of it is like that, too.

00:05:13.399 --> 00:05:16.920
But visualizations are especially like that, I think, because they strive to be

00:05:16.920 --> 00:05:19.119
accessible and seem immediately interpretable.

00:05:19.320 --> 00:05:21.920
I mean, that's what we want when we make visualizations.

00:05:22.140 --> 00:05:25.660
But it's that power that also makes me kind of suspicious, a little bit suspicious

00:05:25.660 --> 00:05:29.420
anyway, of the whole rhetoric that has grown up around them, of their popularity, even

00:05:29.420 --> 00:05:32.339
though I do what I can to encourage that popularity myself.

00:05:34.019 --> 00:05:39.459
And as I say, the whole kind of language around data visualization from sort of

00:05:39.459 --> 00:05:43.540
old stuff like lying with graphs all the way through to more contemporary phrases like

00:05:43.540 --> 00:05:47.859
visual storytelling and things, I'm just a little bit suspicious of that.

00:05:48.260 --> 00:05:51.779
We want our data visualizations to be compelling and we want them to be convincing.

00:05:52.459 --> 00:05:55.019
But we also want them to be trustworthy or we should want that.

00:05:55.019 --> 00:05:57.019
And so we can ask, how can we do that?

00:05:57.019 --> 00:05:59.779
How can we make trustworthy data visualizations?

00:05:59.779 --> 00:06:03.140
And where does our trust in them come from?

00:06:03.179 --> 00:06:04.299
How is it sustained?

00:06:04.859 --> 00:06:09.019
And I think what I want to argue in the talk is that what we find is that the answer

00:06:09.019 --> 00:06:13.739
is not is not really the techniques used in the visualizations themselves or even in

00:06:13.739 --> 00:06:17.540
the software used to make them, even though that's made such tremendous strides over

00:06:17.540 --> 00:06:23.000
the last 20 or even five or six years, these are very useful and important, but

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:26.200
they're not sufficient. And instead, the trustworthiness that we want depends on a

00:06:26.200 --> 00:06:32.299
kind of web of social processes and individual commitments that can't easily be

00:06:32.299 --> 00:06:36.160
automated and that we inevitably rely on.

00:06:36.239 --> 00:06:40.559
And if those processes break down or those commitments are weak, then it won't matter

00:06:40.559 --> 00:06:44.600
how good looking our graphs are or how compelling the stories we seem to tell with

00:06:44.600 --> 00:06:47.040
them can be. So that's what the talk is going to be about.

00:06:48.200 --> 00:06:49.799
It's a very juicy topic for me.

00:06:50.040 --> 00:06:55.160
I love it, especially because I do Tidy Tuesday every week and having 30 minutes to

00:06:55.160 --> 00:07:00.040
create a graph, I am frequently going, hmm, well, I got something done, but is it is

00:07:00.040 --> 00:07:01.600
this trustworthy? Is this good?

00:07:01.600 --> 00:07:05.760
Especially if the information that I'm conveying is something about like health care,

00:07:05.760 --> 00:07:10.480
you know, things that are very, very important and not frivolous like Pokemon or D&D

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:11.779
monsters, which it is this week.

00:07:12.480 --> 00:07:18.839
All right, everybody, rev up your questions for Kieran about data visualization and

00:07:18.839 --> 00:07:20.399
other things that Kieran has mentioned.

00:07:20.760 --> 00:07:22.519
Jonathan, how about you?

00:07:22.799 --> 00:07:24.880
What is your conf talk going to be about?

00:07:26.160 --> 00:07:31.679
So my talk is going to be a little bit of history and a little bit of today and then a

00:07:31.679 --> 00:07:35.899
little bit of tomorrow. So kind of one of those time spanning talks.

00:07:35.920 --> 00:07:41.200
So like I mentioned in my intro a few minutes ago, I worked at RStudio.

00:07:41.220 --> 00:07:45.619
I've been at Posit for quite some time, and so I'm going to reflect a little bit on a

00:07:45.619 --> 00:07:51.739
decade of work on RStudio, kind of the principles that have led it to become the

00:07:52.100 --> 00:07:54.100
standard data science environment for R.

00:07:54.579 --> 00:07:58.940
I'm going to talk a bit about how those same principles developed the basis for

00:07:58.940 --> 00:08:03.739
Positron. I'll talk about Positron for quite a bit, and then I'll probably spend a

00:08:03.739 --> 00:08:08.380
little bit of time kind of looking to the future and talking about some of the ideas

00:08:08.380 --> 00:08:10.459
we have for the future of data science tooling.

00:08:11.980 --> 00:08:15.500
Wonderful. I know that we're probably going to have lots of Positron questions.

00:08:16.420 --> 00:08:18.459
Well, I want to hop right into Slido questions.

00:08:18.459 --> 00:08:23.660
We've got a few here already because Noor asked one that is the exact question that I

00:08:23.660 --> 00:08:27.299
wanted to ask. Noor, not a naive question, as you said in Slido.

00:08:27.540 --> 00:08:30.140
This is great. Are you available to unmute and ask yours?

00:08:31.700 --> 00:08:32.739
Hello.

00:08:33.219 --> 00:08:37.619
Yes, I am not fit for visual consumption, but my voice is here.

00:08:38.599 --> 00:08:44.679
This is more directed towards Jonathan, and I think it's a naive question, even though

00:08:44.679 --> 00:08:51.400
Libby doesn't, but what exactly does a data architect do from your perspective?

00:08:52.039 --> 00:08:53.479
And what is your day-to-day like?

00:08:55.760 --> 00:08:59.640
Yeah, so what is my day-to-day like?

00:08:59.640 --> 00:09:05.719
So I have worked on Positron since really day one.

00:09:06.179 --> 00:09:12.580
And so what an architect does in my role is quite a lot of coding and also quite a lot of

00:09:12.580 --> 00:09:13.739
fitting pieces together.

00:09:14.539 --> 00:09:20.500
So a system as complicated as an IDE has a whole bunch of subsystems.

00:09:20.700 --> 00:09:26.900
So if you think about the pieces that compose a complicated data science IDE like

00:09:26.900 --> 00:09:34.659
Positron, you have a user interface that displays the console and the graphs and charts

00:09:34.679 --> 00:09:39.080
and data grids and your variables viewer and all that stuff.

00:09:39.359 --> 00:09:45.159
You have language execution engines like R and Python that are actually performing the

00:09:45.159 --> 00:09:47.400
computations and then emitting results.

00:09:48.159 --> 00:09:50.799
You have other pieces that are going on.

00:09:50.799 --> 00:09:53.080
You have terminals. You have connections to other systems.

00:09:54.799 --> 00:09:58.239
These systems will often run in a web browser or in a desktop IDE.

00:09:58.260 --> 00:10:04.820
And so an architect's job in many cases is to simply design the way that all those

00:10:04.820 --> 00:10:08.419
processes work together to form a cohesive whole.

00:10:09.260 --> 00:10:13.719
So in the early days of Positron, I spent quite a lot of time just kind of slotting

00:10:13.719 --> 00:10:19.020
pieces in and out to figure out how to build a solid, reliable, robust system that does

00:10:19.020 --> 00:10:20.260
all the things we need it to do.

00:10:21.200 --> 00:10:28.679
And as the product has matured, my job is to be spending a lot more time actually

00:10:29.239 --> 00:10:35.559
writing a lot of middleware and glue code that keeps everything talking to each

00:10:35.559 --> 00:10:40.479
other, as well as writing a bunch of stuff that does individual features on the front

00:10:40.479 --> 00:10:41.320
end and the back end.

00:10:41.320 --> 00:10:47.200
So building UI, building capabilities that connect to R and Python, and then writing

00:10:47.200 --> 00:10:50.159
the systems that make those things talk to each other and work well together.

00:10:51.119 --> 00:10:55.719
Noor, I hope that that answered your question.

00:10:55.719 --> 00:10:56.919
I thought that was a great question.

00:10:56.919 --> 00:11:02.520
I say it's not naive because I don't know instinctively what a data architect does.

00:11:02.679 --> 00:11:07.119
And I've worked with data architects who do very different things.

00:11:07.119 --> 00:11:12.080
I feel like you might have the same title in another company with different functions

00:11:12.080 --> 00:11:13.479
and do something totally different.

00:11:14.320 --> 00:11:18.679
All righty, well, let's move on to Arsenis.

00:11:18.679 --> 00:11:20.659
Arsenis, you had a great question in Slido.

00:11:20.659 --> 00:11:22.739
I would love it if you could unmute and ask that.

00:11:23.380 --> 00:11:24.020
Yeah, sure.

00:11:24.020 --> 00:11:24.539
Thanks, Libby.

00:11:24.539 --> 00:11:25.059
Hey.

00:11:25.179 --> 00:11:30.260
Hey, so thank you, Kieran and Jonathan, for joining us today and chatting with us.

00:11:30.580 --> 00:11:37.940
My question is more for Kieran on this because you mentioned having used S when R

00:11:37.940 --> 00:11:41.700
was S, and I like the history of these languages quite a lot.

00:11:41.979 --> 00:11:46.419
So my question is, what are some of the developments in R that most stand out to

00:11:46.419 --> 00:11:53.280
you versus kind of the original S that maybe a lot of people might not be aware

00:11:53.280 --> 00:11:58.719
of or might've missed, and what are some of the developments that you hope to see

00:11:58.719 --> 00:11:59.919
in the language in the future?

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:03.280
Boy, yeah, there's a lot.

00:12:03.320 --> 00:12:12.119
I mean, it's like 30 years and more of development kind of that is behind that.

00:12:12.760 --> 00:12:15.840
One of the things that changed is that you used to be able to use the underscore

00:12:15.840 --> 00:12:21.979
character as the assignment operator, which made for really terrible readability for

00:12:21.979 --> 00:12:24.900
code, and thankfully that went away.

00:12:25.859 --> 00:12:32.219
I think that it's in the character of R as a language to be constantly trying out

00:12:32.219 --> 00:12:38.580
new things within a sort of more or less structured overall community of the core

00:12:38.580 --> 00:12:41.539
developers and the wider world.

00:12:41.559 --> 00:12:46.400
And so in effect, what you have with R always is this kind of like these stratigraphic

00:12:46.400 --> 00:12:54.200
layers of previous efforts to develop aspects of the language, not all of which hang

00:12:54.200 --> 00:12:55.960
together very well.

00:12:55.960 --> 00:12:59.799
And so that was the main reason, I guess, that sort of Tidyverse and the whole place

00:12:59.799 --> 00:13:08.679
that Posit eventually can be traced back to, that was a real revolution in the

00:13:08.700 --> 00:13:14.940
usability of R for kind of people coming to data science broadly construed or data

00:13:14.940 --> 00:13:17.460
analysis, statistical data analysis for the first time.

00:13:18.940 --> 00:13:23.299
Not that there weren't sort of strictly speaking, there weren't that many things

00:13:23.299 --> 00:13:28.460
that you literally couldn't do before Tidyverse tools came along.

00:13:28.460 --> 00:13:33.700
But the harmonization that it brought really was a big step forward and sort of

00:13:33.719 --> 00:13:40.200
helped streamline things a little bit with all of the usual kind of trade-offs and

00:13:40.200 --> 00:13:43.559
caveats that come with that kind of development.

00:13:43.919 --> 00:13:49.080
And then the other big development, I think, going back to what Jonathan was talking

00:13:49.080 --> 00:13:57.000
about in his role, has kind of been in many ways the tooling, right, whether it's

00:13:57.059 --> 00:14:05.140
IDEs specifically, but then also kind of the ease with which R can talk to other aspects

00:14:05.140 --> 00:14:09.219
of general computing has really improved a great deal.

00:14:10.179 --> 00:14:16.859
So I'm not a software developer, although I do write R packages from time to time.

00:14:16.859 --> 00:14:22.500
And so I don't have extremely strong views on where the language should go or where the

00:14:22.500 --> 00:14:25.780
tooling should go. That's kind of not my area.

00:14:25.780 --> 00:14:32.080
But I do feel like the language as it exists now and the tooling as it exists now is just

00:14:32.080 --> 00:14:36.520
so much better than what we had in the past.

00:14:36.520 --> 00:14:42.340
And we'd like to see that sort of continue both in terms of its sort of flexibility while

00:14:42.340 --> 00:14:47.479
maintaining its core strengths, which have always been sort of it's the language that's

00:14:47.479 --> 00:14:52.919
built for data analysis at its core and builds into it kind of abstractions like the

00:14:52.919 --> 00:14:56.940
humble data frame that a lot of other languages kind of have to work a lot harder to

00:14:56.940 --> 00:15:00.260
integrate into how they work.

00:15:00.539 --> 00:15:07.739
And so between that and if we can continue on that path and maintain the sort of really

00:15:07.739 --> 00:15:11.820
vibrant kind of community that R has always had, then we'll be in good shape, I think.

00:15:13.059 --> 00:15:17.500
Something that Kieran said when I first talked to him that really stood out to me was

00:15:18.299 --> 00:15:22.299
something about like, you know, everyone's kind of worried about Positron, like, oh, it

00:15:22.299 --> 00:15:23.400
changes scary. Right.

00:15:23.599 --> 00:15:29.919
But when you've seen things progress over a large number of years from S to R, you've seen

00:15:29.919 --> 00:15:31.039
all of these changes happen.

00:15:31.039 --> 00:15:35.320
You're a lot less afraid of change because you know that it happens.

00:15:35.320 --> 00:15:37.400
Change happens. Stuff gets better over time.

00:15:37.400 --> 00:15:38.760
And it was such a positive outlook.

00:15:40.719 --> 00:15:43.520
Yeah, I mean, he's been around long enough.

00:15:43.520 --> 00:15:48.760
There's after a while you do you do feel like the sort of negative version of that is saying

00:15:49.140 --> 00:15:52.659
you don't want to turn into sort of a cranky old man yells at cloud.

00:15:52.900 --> 00:15:55.659
Anytime some new thing comes along, I'm real mad about it.

00:15:56.979 --> 00:16:00.500
In almost all of these cases, you know, something comes along and changes.

00:16:00.900 --> 00:16:02.299
It offers some advantages.

00:16:02.299 --> 00:16:05.900
Some people will seize on that and take advantage of it.

00:16:05.900 --> 00:16:08.580
Other people will be like, well, things work fine the way they are for me.

00:16:08.619 --> 00:16:11.940
So if it's not broke, don't fix it.

00:16:12.520 --> 00:16:19.960
But there's room within the overall kind of space of the language and of languages and

00:16:19.960 --> 00:16:24.640
tools generally for exactly that sort of range of reactions.

00:16:24.640 --> 00:16:29.820
It doesn't mean that kind of, you know, people are going to be sort of forced down one road

00:16:29.820 --> 00:16:33.719
rather than another. There's generally kind of a lot of heterogeneity that can persist for a

00:16:33.719 --> 00:16:37.559
very long time, even in the context of kind of innovation and change.

00:16:38.119 --> 00:16:40.880
Right. And good things are coming always.

00:16:41.340 --> 00:16:43.380
It doesn't change, doesn't have to be terrible.

00:16:43.580 --> 00:16:47.179
Well, there was a little discussion going on in the chat that I wanted to call out because

00:16:47.179 --> 00:16:52.179
Zach asked to the chat, like, hey, what do S&R even stand for?

00:16:52.179 --> 00:16:53.500
Like is S for statistics?

00:16:54.340 --> 00:16:57.219
I have always thought, yes, S is like loosely for statistics.

00:16:57.739 --> 00:17:04.020
And for anybody who is curious, my understanding of R, which is reflected in the comments

00:17:04.020 --> 00:17:08.739
here, is that Ross and Robert were the two guys who were working on this.

00:17:08.739 --> 00:17:09.880
And so they both start with R.

00:17:09.880 --> 00:17:11.479
And then, of course, it was S before.

00:17:11.479 --> 00:17:13.079
So let's call it another single letter.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:15.520
Great question, Zach, for the chat.

00:17:15.520 --> 00:17:17.079
And if you ever have any questions for Zach.

00:17:17.079 --> 00:17:20.199
