00:18:07.119 --> 00:18:09.219
But I also have to say, hi, Kieran, it's been a long time.

00:18:09.219 --> 00:18:12.660
It's really fun to see. We should catch up.

00:18:13.900 --> 00:18:15.459
Jonathan, I'm, I'm curious.

00:18:16.500 --> 00:18:18.500
We talk a whole lot and Kieran just mentioned tooling.

00:18:18.880 --> 00:18:24.180
We talk a whole lot about software development, software engineering, informing data

00:18:24.180 --> 00:18:29.660
science. And we see that in practices and, you know, deployment and methods and tools

00:18:29.660 --> 00:18:34.939
and stuff. I'm curious if on the software development side, if you see data science

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:38.920
practices, methods like informing, making software better.

00:18:39.959 --> 00:18:44.000
I've started thinking a lot about, like, what are we what are we pushing back into

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:50.920
software development that might be interesting that that that that we don't see from

00:18:50.920 --> 00:18:53.439
the from the data side or from that from the data science side?

00:18:53.479 --> 00:18:58.520
I'm curious if being at RStudio, Posit, a long time, if that's informing the way you

00:18:58.520 --> 00:18:59.920
think about software development.

00:19:00.900 --> 00:19:08.979
So I'll kind of answer in three parts here, so, so for the first two, I think that there

00:19:08.979 --> 00:19:13.819
has been limited flow in the other direction, probably less than less than you might

00:19:13.819 --> 00:19:19.780
hope. But there are a variety of things that are valuable when doing data science that

00:19:19.780 --> 00:19:24.459
have leaked back in the software engineering world, especially for people who work on

00:19:24.459 --> 00:19:26.020
software that does data science.

00:19:26.920 --> 00:19:31.880
But I will say that like having been part of both communities, like a lot of the back

00:19:31.880 --> 00:19:35.800
flow that I'm seeing is around like number one around iteration.

00:19:36.439 --> 00:19:41.479
Right. So like the when you when you develop software, like it is a very iterative

00:19:41.479 --> 00:19:46.239
process, right? Like, you know, like almost nobody, even in the age of LLMs, can one

00:19:46.239 --> 00:19:47.280
shot an application.

00:19:47.400 --> 00:19:52.119
Right. And so one thing you notice when you watch data scientists work is how iterative

00:19:52.140 --> 00:19:56.699
that work is, like especially when they're doing exploratory data analysis, like that

00:19:56.699 --> 00:20:01.060
process of like iterating, like testing, like there's a there's a loop here, right,

00:20:01.060 --> 00:20:05.420
that you're doing as as you iterate on your and explore your data.

00:20:05.739 --> 00:20:13.900
And that mechanism or like the tools that you use to explore that space are similar to

00:20:13.900 --> 00:20:18.780
the tools that you use at a philosophical level when you're exploring the software

00:20:18.780 --> 00:20:23.119
space. It's like if you watch software engineers kind of explore a new space, if

00:20:23.119 --> 00:20:26.119
they've been informed by data science, you can watch them do kind of the same iterative

00:20:26.119 --> 00:20:28.719
approach. The second is in reproducibility.

00:20:28.719 --> 00:20:33.400
Right. So one of the things that matters a lot to data scientists is making sure that

00:20:33.400 --> 00:20:36.719
the work they do is fully reproducible.

00:20:36.719 --> 00:20:40.800
Like this is one of the original goals of doing code first data science is that it

00:20:40.800 --> 00:20:45.400
generates an artifact, you know, that anybody can use to verify your analysis.

00:20:46.219 --> 00:20:51.780
You know, and I'm very fortunate to work in the world of software engineering in open

00:20:51.780 --> 00:20:57.300
source software, where one of the core values we have at Posit is we want to make our

00:20:57.300 --> 00:21:02.339
software reproducible in the same way that the data science are doing with the software

00:21:02.339 --> 00:21:03.699
is reproducible. Right.

00:21:03.699 --> 00:21:07.380
So, you know, we publish the source code to pretty much everything that we do.

00:21:07.619 --> 00:21:11.219
I can make sure that anybody can kind of build and verify copies of our software.

00:21:11.219 --> 00:21:16.359
We make sure that the environment in which we build the software is documented and

00:21:16.359 --> 00:21:23.119
available to people. So those are those are kind of two examples of practices that have

00:21:23.359 --> 00:21:27.640
kind of crossed the boundary or kind of co-evolved in these two separate communities.

00:21:28.439 --> 00:21:34.280
And then the third one is simply that, like, as we make software for data science, you

00:21:34.280 --> 00:21:38.520
know, and I'll probably talk about this a bit more in my keynote, but that that software

00:21:38.520 --> 00:21:43.540
is informed by the data science community and is built differently than people who are

00:21:43.540 --> 00:21:45.500
writing software for software engineers.

00:21:45.859 --> 00:21:50.500
These two communities have some similar needs, but also some that are some that are quite

00:21:50.500 --> 00:21:57.420
different. So, yeah, not a whole lot of crossover, but a lot of co-evolution and

00:21:57.420 --> 00:21:59.459
certainly some ideas have leaked over.

00:22:00.859 --> 00:22:03.020
Wonderful. Thank you for that great question, Alan.

