one one minute here.

00:22:12.560 --> 00:22:15.119
All right, Lisa, you had a question for Kieran.

00:22:15.119 --> 00:22:16.839
Would you like to unmute and ask that?

00:22:18.680 --> 00:22:20.400
Sure. Lots of you hear me, too.

00:22:20.599 --> 00:22:22.479
Yeah. Yeah.

00:22:22.520 --> 00:22:23.560
Hi, Kieran.

00:22:23.599 --> 00:22:25.280
Great to sort of meet you.

00:22:25.280 --> 00:22:29.680
I think I've read a book or two of yours maybe on DataVis.

00:22:30.339 --> 00:22:37.300
So I'm super curious how to successfully move industry folks from tables of numbers to

00:22:37.300 --> 00:22:40.619
visualizations. And by the way, I'm not anti-tables.

00:22:40.619 --> 00:22:47.900
I just think, you know, let's say a 20 by 100 table of numbers.

00:22:48.459 --> 00:22:51.420
I sort of question what anyone is getting from that.

00:22:51.560 --> 00:22:59.479
So is the is the problem kind of just habits, you think, or are or is it sort of perceived

00:22:59.479 --> 00:23:06.239
differences in the information that's being conveyed that that's behind that resistance?

00:23:06.719 --> 00:23:09.479
Yeah, that's a good question.

00:23:09.520 --> 00:23:15.839
I was kind of hoping maybe your sociologist brain would have the answer.

00:23:15.900 --> 00:23:16.900
Why are they so resistant?

00:23:16.900 --> 00:23:24.420
I think people keep disagreeing with me that, yeah, I think that there is, well, you know.

00:23:26.099 --> 00:23:31.260
There's a lot of. Habit makes a big difference to how organizations work, and established

00:23:31.260 --> 00:23:34.500
practice is very hard to shift, even for good reasons.

00:23:35.380 --> 00:23:40.660
And and I will say that, like, you know, one of the so-called, you know, one of the things

00:23:40.660 --> 00:23:51.640
that I've learned is that, you know, data visualization as a as a technique is is great.

00:23:51.640 --> 00:23:54.160
And it has, you know, I'm all in favor of it.

00:23:54.160 --> 00:23:58.520
And I think in a world where we're giving sort of talks with sides all the time, it's

00:23:58.839 --> 00:24:05.719
much more effective in conveying what it is that you that you want to show than presenting

00:24:05.719 --> 00:24:08.239
a slide full of numbers, for example, can be.

00:24:09.140 --> 00:24:13.099
I I'll say two things about about sort of resistance.

00:24:13.099 --> 00:24:17.540
One is that because if people have been doing it for a long time, it doesn't just mean that

00:24:17.540 --> 00:24:21.560
they're entrenched. It also, you know, for sort of negative reasons, it also means that

00:24:21.560 --> 00:24:26.099
their skills are oriented towards interpreting that artifact like a table, that thing.

00:24:26.900 --> 00:24:31.219
I remember very, very strongly one of my kind of early experiences being trained just as

00:24:31.219 --> 00:24:35.979
a social scientist was encountering people, advisors and teachers who could just look

00:24:35.979 --> 00:24:40.780
at a table like of models or statistical data or summaries and see things kind of

00:24:40.780 --> 00:24:44.640
immediately in the table because they've been looking at them for years and they would

00:24:44.640 --> 00:24:47.479
just kind of put their finger like, look, that that coefficient there, what something

00:24:47.479 --> 00:24:51.520
is wrong with that, you know, that standard error or whatever it is like they would they

00:24:51.520 --> 00:24:54.920
just had that ability. And it was because they'd looked at like thousands of these

00:24:54.920 --> 00:24:57.319
things, hundreds of thousands of these things over a very long time.

00:24:57.599 --> 00:25:02.079
And so then if you're asking people to shift from that habit to sort of some new skill,

00:25:02.079 --> 00:25:04.859
then that can be that that can be tricky.

00:25:05.920 --> 00:25:10.780
And they too were raised in a you know, those people were trained in a world where people

00:25:10.780 --> 00:25:15.979
weren't presenting to audiences in a it was it was instead, you know, here's here's

00:25:15.979 --> 00:25:20.339
the here's the paper and a handout maybe that you could sort of look at for a while

00:25:20.339 --> 00:25:23.939
while the talk was being given as opposed to a world of slides.

00:25:23.939 --> 00:25:29.020
And so so then tables of data translate quite poorly to

00:25:29.020 --> 00:25:31.040
slides for that kind of person.

00:25:31.800 --> 00:25:33.160
One of the things that I.

00:25:34.839 --> 00:25:39.959
Emphasize a lot, and it's also something that people don't grasp all that

00:25:40.239 --> 00:25:43.680
straightforwardly when they're learning data visualization, is that an awful lot of

00:25:43.680 --> 00:25:47.160
visualization that that we do, in effect.

00:25:48.199 --> 00:25:52.900
Is structured the way that a table is structured, this is true of kind of small

00:25:52.900 --> 00:25:57.439
multiples, but also even simple things like like a huge amount of time, we have kind of

00:25:57.439 --> 00:26:01.859
some sort of we have some sort of continuous measure, a number and some sort of

00:26:01.859 --> 00:26:06.680
category broken out by some sort of set of categories, whether it's, you know, scores

00:26:06.680 --> 00:26:11.819
by country or by state or divisions of an organization or sales categories, whatever

00:26:11.819 --> 00:26:14.300
it is, and then some quantity associated with those.

00:26:14.660 --> 00:26:19.260
And one of the simplest things you can do that's extremely underrated and very effective

00:26:19.540 --> 00:26:22.900
for visualizations is to try and turn your visualization into something more like a

00:26:22.900 --> 00:26:24.020
table that people can read.

00:26:24.239 --> 00:26:29.400
Often, that's as simple as put the categorical stuff on the Y axis and not the X axis, so

00:26:29.400 --> 00:26:31.959
people don't have to turn their heads or, you know, to waste your time sort of figuring

00:26:31.959 --> 00:26:36.239
out how to put the labels at 45 degrees so that they're that they're readable.

00:26:36.500 --> 00:26:40.599
And instead, put the continuous quantity on the X axis and put the put the categorical

00:26:40.599 --> 00:26:41.680
quantity on the Y axis.

00:26:41.680 --> 00:26:46.319
And then suddenly it's just a table again, except that now there are dots or lengths

00:26:46.319 --> 00:26:48.119
which are easy to to grasp.

00:26:48.119 --> 00:26:56.660
And so the I think the I think the similarities between tabular layouts and and graphs are

00:26:56.660 --> 00:26:59.939
easy to underestimate and that one way to get people who are used to looking at tables

00:26:59.939 --> 00:27:05.900
of numbers to over to the visualization stuff is to help them realize that effective

00:27:05.900 --> 00:27:10.619
visualizations are often just tables of visual quantities rather than just tables of

00:27:10.619 --> 00:27:13.459
numbers and are easy to easier to read for that reason.

00:27:14.939 --> 00:27:15.540
I love it.

00:27:16.160 --> 00:27:20.599
There's so much good conversation happening in the chat, if you are watching this or

00:27:20.599 --> 00:27:23.839
listening to this later and you're not here live in the chat, you're missing so much

00:27:24.400 --> 00:27:29.000
because we have a community full of really smart and talented individuals who are giving

00:27:29.000 --> 00:27:30.400
us all of their their takes.

00:27:30.479 --> 00:27:34.239
Some of my takes are if you have somebody who can't let go of a table, you could do

00:27:34.239 --> 00:27:39.180
color mapped tables where bigger values have a different color or or something like

00:27:39.180 --> 00:27:41.680
that. I it's a go between at least.

00:27:41.680 --> 00:27:45.579
Right. So you can see visually as your values diverge.

00:27:46.260 --> 00:27:47.619
All right. Awesome question, Lisa.

