00:27:49.260 --> 00:27:52.380
Let's go to Zach's question.

00:27:52.380 --> 00:27:54.739
And Zach has an asterisk in his.

00:27:54.739 --> 00:27:56.060
That means Libby, ask it for me.

00:27:56.060 --> 00:27:59.339
So this is for Jonathan, I think.

00:27:59.939 --> 00:28:03.060
What? Oh, Jonathan, this is the question you've been dreading.

00:28:03.060 --> 00:28:10.140
Are you ready? What are your long term goals with Positron and do you think it might

00:28:10.140 --> 00:28:12.280
eventually replace RStudio?

00:28:14.040 --> 00:28:16.400
I did know someone was going to ask this.

00:28:17.719 --> 00:28:20.920
Thanks, Zach. It's a great question.

00:28:22.040 --> 00:28:24.000
So I'll answer the first part.

00:28:24.040 --> 00:28:28.800
So our long term goals for Positron is to really make it the best IDE for working with

00:28:28.800 --> 00:28:31.000
data in any language.

00:28:31.359 --> 00:28:39.239
So Positron is built in such a way that the R and Python subsystems that we added to

00:28:39.239 --> 00:28:41.099
Positron are just extensions.

00:28:41.300 --> 00:28:43.699
Right. So if you think about the again, I'm an architect.

00:28:43.739 --> 00:28:46.459
Think about the overall way the Positron is composed.

00:28:47.020 --> 00:28:52.140
We built it so that anybody can write a plug in for like a new language or new

00:28:52.140 --> 00:28:53.540
capabilities to Positron.

00:28:53.619 --> 00:29:00.180
So like Positron as a core is going to have the really like first class, like

00:29:00.180 --> 00:29:05.099
hopefully best in the world at being like a data science workbench that will be

00:29:05.119 --> 00:29:09.880
extensible to new languages and new capabilities over time and continue to evolve

00:29:09.880 --> 00:29:11.119
as the industry does.

00:29:12.719 --> 00:29:16.319
So for the second part of that question, is this eventually going to replace RStudio?

00:29:16.640 --> 00:29:18.040
The answer is probably not.

00:29:18.400 --> 00:29:20.760
So a couple of things to keep in mind here.

00:29:20.760 --> 00:29:27.079
So the first is that Positron is not and will never be a superset of RStudio.

00:29:27.439 --> 00:29:29.640
So it does not have all of RStudio's features.

00:29:29.680 --> 00:29:32.319
It won't ever have all the features that are currently in RStudio.

00:29:32.800 --> 00:29:34.680
And it makes a different set of tradeoffs.

00:29:34.699 --> 00:29:39.180
So like I want you to think about things that are more general and then more

00:29:39.180 --> 00:29:44.180
specific, like you can get a lot more power and capability if you're willing to make

00:29:44.180 --> 00:29:46.900
your tool fit for a very specific use.

00:29:47.420 --> 00:29:53.180
You can also get a lot more breadth for your tool at the expense of making it like a

00:29:53.180 --> 00:29:55.819
little bit awkward for more specific use cases.

00:29:56.260 --> 00:30:00.020
And this is one of the things we're really wrestling with as we develop Positron is,

00:30:00.719 --> 00:30:05.319
there are people that are coming from RStudio or from VS Code or PyCharm or Dataspot

00:30:05.319 --> 00:30:11.599
or whatever, and people who are using their tools in a very deep way, it's difficult

00:30:11.599 --> 00:30:18.560
to make one tool, one generic data workbench that serves all these very specific

00:30:18.560 --> 00:30:21.319
needs without turning into a very complicated piece of software.

00:30:21.959 --> 00:30:24.280
So RStudio is very, very fit.

00:30:24.280 --> 00:30:30.000
It's evolved almost like a river rock, just smoothed out by decades of work to

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:33.180
be very, very good at specific R-based workflows.

00:30:33.180 --> 00:30:38.140
And honestly, even as someone who has worked on Positron for years now, I don't

00:30:38.140 --> 00:30:43.099
think Positron will ever be as good as RStudio for those specific use cases, simply

00:30:43.099 --> 00:30:48.099
again, because you can't take something so generic and make it work as well as

00:30:48.099 --> 00:30:50.420
something that is fit for a more specific purpose.

00:30:51.380 --> 00:30:56.619
So we think if you work for R and Python together or just Python, you'll be a lot

00:30:56.619 --> 00:31:01.520
happier in Positron because it's so much better at multi-language stuff.

00:31:01.680 --> 00:31:04.719
It has much deeper ID capabilities because it's built on VS Code.

00:31:04.719 --> 00:31:06.760
A couple of people in the chat have pointed that out.

00:31:07.920 --> 00:31:14.000
And also, we are continuing to invest in RStudio with a lot of the ideas that we

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:15.800
have germinated in Positron.

00:31:15.839 --> 00:31:20.479
So if, for example, if you use a really recent build of RStudio, you'll notice

00:31:21.160 --> 00:31:25.640
that it has much better treatment for errors and warnings and messages in the

00:31:25.640 --> 00:31:30.420
console, which is basically derived and pioneered from work that we did in

00:31:30.420 --> 00:31:31.260
Positron.

00:31:32.140 --> 00:31:38.540
Same thing, for example, we're building some tools for R that run inside of

00:31:38.540 --> 00:31:42.939
Positron, and we're pulling those tools back into RStudio to improve the R

00:31:42.939 --> 00:31:43.859
experience there.

00:31:44.459 --> 00:31:46.739
One of those tools, for example, is called AIR.

00:31:46.859 --> 00:31:52.900
It's an incredibly fast code formatter and server for the R language.

00:31:52.920 --> 00:31:58.000
And it's native in Positron, but also you can now hook it up to RStudio in a recent

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:01.560
release to have it format your R code beautifully every time you save it.

00:32:02.400 --> 00:32:06.599
So we're seeing a lot of cross-pollination between the IDEs, which we think is

00:32:06.599 --> 00:32:06.959
great.

